HOUSE BILL 191
I3, I4 6lr1003
(PRE–FILED)
By: Delegate Wims
Requested: September 29, 2025
Introduced and read first time: January 14, 2026
Assigned to: Economic Matters
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
House action: Adopted
Read second time: March 9, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Consumer Protection – Retail Transactions for Essential Consumer Goods –
3 Cash Payments
4 FOR the purpose of prohibiting a merchant, in a certain transaction, from prohibiting a
5 person from making a cash payment to purchase a an essential consumer good or
6 service, requiring a person to purchase a an essential consumer good or service by
7 using a credit or debit card, or charging or collecting from a person a fee higher price
8 than for an equivalent cashless transaction for making a cash payment for the
9 purchase of a an essential consumer good or service, subject to certain exceptions;
10 establishing that a violation of this Act is an unfair, abusive, or deceptive trade
11 practice subject to certain enforcement and penalty provisions under the Maryland
12 Consumer Protection Act; and generally relating to retail cash transactions for
13 essential consumer goods.
14 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
15 Article – Commercial Law
16 Section 13–301(14)(xlvii)
17 Annotated Code of Maryland
18 (2025 Replacement Volume)
19 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
20 Article – Commercial Law
21 Section 13–301(14)(xlviii)
22 Annotated Code of Maryland
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *hb0191*

2 HOUSE BILL 191
1 (2025 Replacement Volume)
2 BY adding to
3 Article – Commercial Law
4 Section 13–301(14)(xlix) and 14–1330
5 Annotated Code of Maryland
6 (2025 Replacement Volume)
7 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
8 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
9 Article – Commercial Law
10 13–301.
11 Unfair, abusive, or deceptive trade practices include any:
12 (14) Violation of a provision of:
13 (xlvii) Title 14, Subtitle 50 of this article; [or]
14 (xlviii) Section 13–411.1(c)(2) of the Transportation Article; or
15 (XLIX) SECTION 14–1330 OF THIS ARTICLE; OR
16 14–1330.
17 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION, THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
18 INDICATED.
19 (2) “CONSUMER GOODS” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 13–101 OF
20 THIS ARTICLE.
21 (3) “ESSENTIAL CONSUMER GOOD” MEANS:
22 (I) FOOD, INCLUDING HUMAN AND ANIMAL FOOD;
23 (II) WATER, INCLUDING ICE, AND OTHER BEVERAGES;
24 (III) PERSONAL HYGIENE PRODUCTS, INCLUDING TOILETRIES
25 AND CLEANING PRODUCTS;
26 (IV) HEALTH PRODUCTS, INCLUDING MEDICINE, MEDICAL
27 SUPPLIES AND EQUIPMENT, AND PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT; AND
28 (V) FUEL.

HOUSE BILL 191 3
1 (4) “MERCHANT MERCHANT” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 13–101
2 OF THIS ARTICLE.
3 (5) “RETAIL ESTABLISHMENT” MEANS AN ESTABLISHMENT THAT
4 SELLS CONSUMER GOODS TO THE PUBLIC.
5 (B) (1) THIS SECTION APPLIES ONLY TO AN IN–PERSON RETAIL
6 TRANSACTION AT A RETAIL ESTABLISHMENT TOTALING AT LEAST $5 AND LESS THAN
7 $300.
8 (2) THIS SECTION DOES NOT APPLY TO:
9 (I) A TELEPHONE, MAIL, OR INTERNET TRANSACTION; OR
10 (II) A VENDING MACHINE OR KIOSK TRANSACTION; OR
11 (III) A TRANSACTION WITH A MERCHANT THAT SELLS TO THE
12 PUBLIC PRIMARILY:
13 1. FOOD OR BEVERAGES FOR ON–PREMISES
14 CONSUMPTION; OR
15 2. A LIMITED VARIETY OF GOURMET OR SPECIALTY
16 FOODS, INCLUDING CHEESES, FRUITS, NUTS, CANDY, SPICES, AND OILS.
17 (II) A TRANSACTION TO PAY TO PARK A VEHICLE IN:
18 1. A PARKING LOT OR GARAGE; OR
19 2. A METERED PARKING SPACE.
20 (C) A EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN SUBSECTION (D) OF THIS SECTION, A
21 MERCHANT MAY NOT:
22 (1) PROHIBIT A PERSON FROM MAKING A CASH PAYMENT TO
23 PURCHASE A AN ESSENTIAL CONSUMER GOOD OR SERVICE;
24 (2) REQUIRE A PERSON TO USE A CREDIT OR DEBIT CARD TO
25 PURCHASE A AN ESSENTIAL CONSUMER GOOD OR SERVICE; OR
26 (3) CHARGE OR COLLECT FROM A PERSON A HIGHER PRICE THAN
27 CHARGED OR COLLECTED FOR AN EQUIVALENT CASHLESS TRANSACTION, WHETHER

4 HOUSE BILL 191
1 OR NOT THE DIFFERENCE IN PRICE IS DESCRIBED AS A FEE, FOR MAKING A CASH
2 PAYMENT FOR THE PURCHASE OF A AN ESSENTIAL CONSUMER GOOD OR SERVICE.
3 (D) A MERCHANT MAY PROHIBIT A PERSON FROM MAKING A CASH PAYMENT
4 FOR THE PURCHASE OF A CONSUMER GOOD:
5 (1) IN A CASH DENOMINATION GREATER THAN $20; OR
6 (2) IF THE MERCHANT:
7 (I) PROVIDES AND MAINTAINS A DEVICE ON THE PREMISES OF
8 THE ESTABLISHMENT THAT CONVERTS CASH INTO A PREPAID CARD THAT A PERSON
9 MAY USE TO PURCHASE A CONSUMER GOOD AT THE ESTABLISHMENT;
10 (II) DOES NOT CHARGE ANY FEE OR REQUIRE A DEPOSIT; AND
11 (III) IF THE DEVICE MALFUNCTIONS OR BECOMES INOPERABLE,
12 ACCEPTS PAYMENT IN CASH IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SECTION UNTIL THE
13 DEVICE RESUMES NORMAL OPERATIONS.
14 (D) (E) A VIOLATION OF THIS SECTION IS:
15 (1) AN UNFAIR, ABUSIVE, OR DECEPTIVE TRADE PRACTICE WITHIN
16 THE MEANING OF TITLE 13 OF THIS ARTICLE; AND
17 (2) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN SUBSECTION (E) (F) OF THIS SECTION,
18 SUBJECT TO THE ENFORCEMENT AND PENALTY PROVISIONS CONTAINED IN TITLE
19 13 OF THIS ARTICLE.
20 (E) (F) (1) SECTIONS 13–410(A) AND (B) AND 13–411 OF THIS ARTICLE
21 DO NOT APPLY TO A VIOLATION OF THIS SECTION.
22 (2) THE DIVISION OF CONSUMER PROTECTION OF THE OFFICE OF
23 THE ATTORNEY GENERAL SHALL PROVIDE A MERCHANT WHO VIOLATES THIS
24 SECTION WITH AT LEAST TWO SEPARATE OPPORTUNITIES TO COMPLY WITH THE
25 REQUIREMENTS OF THIS SECTION.
26 (3) (I) A MERCHANT WHO VIOLATES THIS SECTION AFTER TWO
27 SEPARATE OPPORTUNITIES TO COMPLY UNDER PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS
28 SUBSECTION IS SUBJECT TO A FINE NOT EXCEEDING $5,000 $500 FOR EACH
29 VIOLATION.

HOUSE BILL 191 5
1 (II) A MERCHANT WHO VIOLATES THIS SECTION AFTER HAVING
2 BEEN FINED UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF THIS PARAGRAPH IS SUBJECT TO A FINE
3 NOT EXCEEDING $10,000 $1,000 FOR EACH SUBSEQUENT VIOLATION.
4 (III) THE FINES PROVIDED FOR IN SUBPARAGRAPHS (I) AND (II)
5 OF THIS PARAGRAPH:
6 1. ARE CIVIL PENALTIES RECOVERABLE IN
7 ACCORDANCE WITH § 13–410(C) OF THIS ARTICLE; AND
8 2. SHALL BE SET IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 13–410(D) OF
9 THIS ARTICLE.
10 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
11 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
